snippet.textDisplay:
This is gonna be long but I hope some people can relate...
Looking back on my childhood let’s say from 7-13 I noticed one version of Kobe, not two, and that was greatness. Up until that point around 7 I never really followed basketball because my dad didn’t and I still don’t to this day. At that time Kobe was one of many guys who showed me I could do something I never thought I could do and that was shoot a basketball with only one hand to use. Growing up I watched games here and there but there was one constant, greatness. He did everything he could to make his teammates better players. For that I say thank you Mamba, I played ball for 5 years before stopping in part due to you. You inspired me to have fun when it’s all said and done. And I hope all of us can agree that sports should bring society together not tear it apart. RIP Kobe, Gianna and the seven others who perished on Sunday, my heart breaks over it.

snippet.textDisplay:
Beeing from Europe and reading and watching so much the last days about Kobe I totally understand what this extrodinary man meant to all of you. And HE was an ambassador for the world to make us see there's a different America than a hateful president.
Also someone who didn't care if " his" community was upset when marrying a Latino woman..a role model for anyone showing that it should be about love and not colour or race. He was what is most important and makes a real role model teaching the ppl that you have to be true to yourself no matter what. THIS is what we need to see in the rest of the world. And yes..we see it in music and sport stars...Muhamad Ali...refusing to join Vietnam war..giving up his medal for that. Because he was true to himself. And will forever remain in our hearts.
The question remains : Why do all these important people have to die so young ??
Kobe was and is amazing, speaking Italian and Spanish..yes, that's also another way to show and receive respect..his daughters have names, probably according to his love for Italy..and the youngest one even named after the Italian island Capri ?!
What an incredible man and loss for you and the world.
The only thing which is consoling : he was always there for his family..they all look SO happy and had those beautiful years together.
No fake smiles for money..just happy.
So from over here we send our condolence and please..whatever the protocol is : let Obama speak at his funeral service. Not Trump.

snippet.textDisplay: I honestly believe Colin's reassessment about Kobe Bryant entire basketball career is perhaps one of his best and deepest discussions ever. I was definitely moved by his speech about Kobe. I and I'm sure as well as others can remember how Kobe played with the Lakers during his rookie season. Many true basketball fans had the privilege and opportunity to watch Kobe play at about 17 years of age to his very last game. My best memory of Kobe even prior to the unfortunate tragedy was watching Kobe come off the bench and emphatically throw down a powerful dunk during a game against the Utah Jazz during his rookie season. I remembered watching Kobe shoot an air ball against the Jazz during that Western Conference Semi Final game back in 1997. And I remembered the stinging criticisms by so called experts. But then, I remembered Kobe and Shaq winning their 1st NBA championship together. Then watching Kobe make so many game winning baskets at the end. And then finally, watching Kobe score 60 points in his final game. I wasn't a Lakers fan, but damn, I so enjoyed watching Kobe play. Whenever I would buy a limited season's Orlando Magic game package each year, I always requested to make sure the "Lakers game" was included in the limited amount of game tickets I purchased. Watching Kobe live was so worth the investment. Since the news, the feeling has been numb. Because as a basketball fan, I always enjoyed watching Kobe on TV and definitely live. The main things I say in prayer is: For comfort to the entire Bryant family, give my support to Lakers fans during these tough times, and also say: Thank you Kobe! Your legacy will continue.
